524 soldiers dismissed from the Nigerian Army over offenses committed during counter insurgency operations have pleaded with the Chief of Army Staff (COAS) Lieutenant General Tukur Buratai to pardon and reinstate them back in Service.The Chief Commissioner, Public Complaints Commission (PCC), Emmanuel Ogbole presented their pardon plea on Tuesday during a meeting with Buratai at the Army Headquarters Abuja.Ogbole who submitted case files of the 524 dismissed soldiers to the Army Chief said the ex-soldiers had approached the Commission to intervene on their behalf.He said: "In summary, we are not here to take any decision on the issue; we are here to transmit their complaints which were recorded and documented for us to you."He added that: "This is to enable you look into them and take the appropriate action in the best interest of the Nigerian army and the nation at large."In his remarks, Buratai said the case of each dismissed soldier would be reviewed in the best interest of the Army and the Nation.He said: "The complaints of 524 ex-soldiers which you presented to me are going to be studied; we will look at each case on its merit."He added that: "I assure that they are going to be resolved in the best interest of the Nigerian army and in the best interest of our country."He also said: "We know that 524 soldiers is almost a battalion and we will definitely feel the impact of these guys but notwithstanding, we will still look at their cases critically based on their merits in the interest of our service and the country."The Army in 2014 dismissed 5,000 soldiers over offences committed during counter insurgency operations in the North East.Later, over 3,000 of them were pardoned and redeployed to fight BokoHaram insurgents in the North East.Their cases were reviewed in Kaduna by a military panel Presided by the General Officer Commanding, 1 Division, Major General Adeniyi Oyebade.Tags: 524 dismissed soldiers plead reinstatement